[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is one of the most underrated AI breakthroughs so far. These researchers made an AI that can understand the code of life, DNA. In fact, they can use this to detect cancer or other diseases, or it can even predict the effects of'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'genetic mutations, and it can even generate the complete DNA of a living thing. The implications of this are wild. This technology could help scientists engineer better crops and unlock new solutions for energy and food'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'security. And this is also great for personalized medicine. We could even use this to design entirely new species or even make ourselves better. In this video, I\'m going to break down exactly how they did this, how it works, and'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some insane findings from this project. Now, this is a very technical paper, but as always, I\'m going to break this down into simple terms so that anyone can understand. Let\'s jump right in. Now, to understand what they did in this paper,'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s start with the basics. You see, current AI models that we use today like ChatGPT and Gemini, these are large language models. They\'re designed to do really good at understanding and outputting natural language. That\'s why'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it can generate a beautiful poem or a flawless essay, or even do a full medical research report for you. But, here\'s the interesting question. Instead of the natural language that you and I'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use to communicate, you know what else is similar? DNA, or the language of life. What if we took the same logic from these large language models and apply it to train an AI that can understand and generate DNA? Well,'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s exactly what these researchers did. So, the paper is called Geno modeling and design across all domains of life with Evo 2. And this was published recently in Nature, which is like the most prestigious scientific'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'journal in the world. Now, before we dive into why this is so important, we first need to understand what DNA is. You see, DNA is like the instruction manual for life. Inside almost every cell in every living thing, there\'s DNA,'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it stores information needed to build and run the organism. Now, DNA is made of only four letters, G, C, A, or T. And these letters bond in pairs. So,'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'G bonds with C and A bonds with T and vice versa. So, from this bonding, it creates two strands like this, which winds together in a spiral or double helix shape like this. So, this is the'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'classic DNA shape that you might be familiar with. Now, the sequence of these letters is what contains the instructions of life. It encodes thousands of traits and biological processes. For example, for humans, this'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'includes eye color, height, risk of disease, our immune system, how we metabolize, and more. It\'s the blueprint for how living things function and stay alive. All right, now, back to this paper. Here, they created this Evo 2'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'biological foundation model trained on 9 trillion DNA base pairs. So, this is actually very similar to large language models like ChatGPT, but instead of'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'being trained on all the data from the internet, this Evo 2 was trained on 9 trillion DNA base pairs. Specifically, they trained it on a data set called Open Genome 2. And this data set'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'essentially takes millions of diverse living things from across the entire spectrum of life and puts their DNA into a massive digital library. So, as you can see, this includes everything from'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bacteria, plants, fungi, and animals, including, of course, humans. The total size of this is like 9 trillion DNA base pairs. So, afterwards, they used all this DNA to train an AI model. And'

[03:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here\'s the technical detail that really stands out. Here, it says that this Evo 2 model has a million token context window with single nucleotide resolution. In simple terms, that means'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the AI can hold 1 million DNA letters in its prompt or working memory at once. Now, why would we need that? After all, a single gene might only be a few thousand letters long. Shouldn\'t that be'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enough? The problem is that biology almost never works in isolation. Here\'s an example. You see, a gene, which is just a section of DNA, might contain the instructions to do something, but whether that gene is actually activated,'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or how strongly it\'s executed, or when it turns on, often depends on other regions of DNA called regulatory elements. And these elements aren\'t always nearby. They might be hundreds of thousands of letters away along the DNA'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'strand. So, the instructions and the controls can be separated by enormous distances. If the model\'s context window is small, say only a few hundred thousand tokens, it might not be able to'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'capture all the relevant parts of a DNA strand. Because this new Evo 2 has a much larger million token context window, it can understand context across DNA a lot better. Now, holding that much'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'information is one thing, but actually being able to understand, remember, and analyze all this data is something else. To prove their system could actually handle a million DNA letters at once, the researchers ran a simple but brutal'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'test, something called a needle in a haystack test. It\'s a very standard test in AI, and basically, they generated a completely random and meaningless sequence of 1 million DNA letters. That\'s the haystack. Then, they took a'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very specific 100-letter sequence and hid it somewhere inside this massive random jumble of letters. This 100-letter sequence is the needle, and they asked Evo 2 to find it. And in short, Evo 2 was able to find it'

[05:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'perfectly. This proves that it\'s not just skimming the sequence or forgetting stuff in this 1 million-letter sequence. It\'s actually reading and retaining the entire thing. So, at this point, we know a few things. We know this model was'

[05:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trained on 9 trillion DNA letters across the entire spectrum of life from extreme bacteria to human cells. We know that it can remember what it reads even if it\'s given a million letters. But, here\'s the deeper question. Can it actually'

[06:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recognize patterns? Can it actually understand the language of DNA? You see, when Evo 2 was trained, it wasn\'t given any labels or answers. It was never told that this particular sequence of DNA triggers a disease, or this one is a'

[06:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mutation that could kill the cell, or that this one, for example, controls leaf color. The model never received these labels or answers. It simply read raw, unlabeled DNA like this. So, how'

[06:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can we tell whether it actually understands DNA? This is where a concept called zero-shot prediction comes in. Zero-shot means the AI can answer something without being explicitly'

[06:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trained on it. But, that raises an obvious question. If the model was never taught what a disease is, how could it possibly know that a certain snippet of DNA would cause disease? The answer lies in evolution. If a genetic sequence is'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'absolutely essential for life, for example, the proteins that allow a cell to generate energy, evolution tends to keep that sequence from change. You see, all the living things in this data set'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are alive because its DNA works and is functional. If a mutation messed up the DNA in a way that could cause disease or death, well, that organism dies, and that mutation wouldn\'t appear in this gene pool. So, over millions of years of'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'evolution, this process leaves a clear signal in the data. When Evo 2 reads these 9 trillion DNA letters from across the entire spectrum of life, it begins to notice these patterns. If it notices'

[07:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the exact same sequence of DNA in many different species, it would signal that the sequence is probably very important. And conversely, if it has never seen a sequence before in this spectrum of life, it might mean that that sequence'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'could be harmful or cause death. Anyways, the researchers had to prove this. They had to show that Evo 2 actually understood the language of DNA. So, to test it, they took a real DNA sequence and changed one letter and then'

[07:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'asked the model a simple question. Based on your understanding, how likely will this DNA exist in nature? If Evo assigns an extremely low probability, the model essentially is raising a red flag. It\'s'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'saying like this mutation is probably harmful because it wouldn\'t exist in nature. Well, when researchers tested Evo 2 this way, they found some incredible things. The model was recognizing very specific biological'

[08:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'signals without ever being taught this. For example, it correctly identified mutations in start codons and stop codons. To understand why this matters, we need to briefly look at how cells'

[08:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'read DNA. You see, DNA is interpreted in groups of three letters called codons. Now, a start codon, usually the sequence ATG, tells the cell\'s machinery where to begin building a protein. It basically'

[08:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'means start here. A stop codon does the opposite. It tells the cell when to stop building. So, if you mutate the start codon, in other words, if you mess up the letters, the protein is never'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'produced. And if you mutate the stop codon, then the cell just keeps working and working far past the intended endpoint. It just produces something that often does not work. So, when scientists added mutations to either the'

[09:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'start or stop codons, Evo 2 was able to correctly flag this mutation as highly destructive, which is correct. And it was even able to understand more subtle things. So, here\'s another insane'

[09:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finding. The researchers found that the model could identify things like the Shine-Dalgarno sequence and the Kozak sequence. Now, what on earth are these? Think of them as like landing pads for the cell\'s protein-building machinery.'

[09:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You see, before a protein can be made, something called a ribosome has to attach to it at exactly the right location, and if it docks in the wrong place, the entire protein might not be built correctly, or even at all. So, the'

[09:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cell has to also code up this a pad region, and for bacteria, this region is called the Shine-Dalgarno sequence. And then for more complex organisms such as humans and plants, this sequence is'

[10:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called the Kozak sequence. These sequences sit basically next to the start of the gene and basically guide the ribosome to the correct starting point. Without them, the ribosome might simply drift past this and never latch'

[10:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'onto it to make a protein. What\'s remarkable is that the AI also figured out these landing pads purely from context. If the scientists added mutations in these areas, the AI was able to successfully flag this as highly'

[10:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'damaging. And there\'s more. It also figured out the difference between what is called a synonymous mutation as well as a frameshift mutation. Let\'s explain these in simple terms. So, a synonymous'

[10:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mutation is when you change a single letter of DNA, but because of the redundancy of the genetic code and because it\'s just one change, it doesn\'t really mess anything up. So, when Evo 2 was shown these mutations, it recognized'

[10:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them and said, "This is fine. It\'s a high likelihood of survival." But a frameshift mutation is different. It\'s catastrophic. You see, DNA is read in chunks of three. So, if you insert or delete just one single letter, every'

[11:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'single three-letter chunk downstream is shifted by one. So, the entire rest of the sequence becomes messed up. Well, when Evo 2 was shown these types of mutations, it was also able to correctly say that these would be severely'

[11:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'damaging. So, as you can see, Evo 2 didn\'t just memorize letters. It actually reverse-engineered how DNA works without ever being taught anything. And it gets even crazier. The researchers did an even more challenging'

[11:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'test called the ciliate code test. You see, for most life on Earth, the sequence TGA is a stop codon, a universal stop sign that tells the cell to stop building a protein. But biology loves exceptions, and there\'s a group of'

[11:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'organisms called ciliates that evolved a slightly different genetic pattern. In their DNA, TGA doesn\'t mean stop. It actually means keep going, just for them. Previous AI models that were'

[12:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trained on DNA would completely fail this test. If they were given ciliate DNA and asked about TGA, the AI models would all say that this is a stop sign, which is not correct. But the remarkable thing about Evo 2 is that because it has'

[12:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a million token context window, because it can understand DNA across all of life, it\'s able to inspect this entire ciliate DNA first and given its context, it\'s able to determine that TGA inside'

[12:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this was not a stop codon. Note that the researchers never told it that this DNA belongs to this organism called a ciliate. The AI also never learned that this belongs to a ciliate or what a'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ciliate even is. Yet it inferred this from its understanding of the grammar of DNA. Now, so far, we\'ve talked about tests on bacteria and other microorganisms, but if this model truly understands the language of life, then'

[12:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in theory, it should also work with human DNA as well, right? And that\'s exactly what the researchers tested next. I\'ve been covering the best image and video generators, and it can get very overwhelming. Fortunately,'

[13:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Higgsfield, the sponsor of this video, brings everything together all in one place. From leading image and video generation models to AI cinematic workflows. The idea here is to bring more of a filmmaking workflow to AI'

[13:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video creation. Instead of you just typing a prompt and hoping for the best, you actually follow a creative pipeline. Cast your actor, build the scene, and direct the shot. It starts with Soulcast, which is Higgsfield\'s AI actor'

[13:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'creation system. Instead of prompting random faces every time, you can design fully customizable characters that stay visually consistent across your scenes. You can define their genre, age,'

[13:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'identity, physical features, clothing style, and more. Next comes Soul Cinema, which generates cinematic grade images to build your scenes. The model focuses heavily on lighting, composition, and'

[13:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'textures, so the outputs look like films instead of AI slop. Once your characters and scenes are ready, you can move everything into Cinema Studio 2, which is where the actual video direction'

[14:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happens. This works like a miniature film studio where you can create multi-shot sequences, control the speed and the camera motion, or you can even define start and end frames, and the system generates the intermediate motion'

[14:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automatically, essentially filling in the animation. All of this makes Higgsfield one of the first platforms to truly connect characters, cinematic image generation, and video direction in one seamless workflow. Whether you\'re'

[14:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'making short films, cinematic ads, music videos, or any other content, the entire process can happen inside one tool. If you want to try it yourself, check out Higgsfield using the link in the description below.'

[14:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This brings us to the third major section of the paper called human variant effect prediction. And this could directly affect real human patients. Here\'s what they did. The researchers took a huge genetics data'

[15:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'set called ClinVar, which is basically a database where doctors record human DNA variations and classify them. For example, some DNA variants are labeled pathogenic, meaning they cause disease,'

[15:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and others are labeled benign, meaning they have no measurable impact on health. Now, the researchers specifically targeted the genes BRCA from this data set. And these are very important genes, which you might have'

[15:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'heard of before, because certain mutations within these genes can drastically increase a person\'s risk of breast and ovarian cancer. Imagine you\'re a doctor and you have the DNA report of your patient, and you\'re'

[15:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looking through the BRCA genes to see if there are any mutations. A small subtle change could be completely harmless, or it could mean cancer, which is obviously life-threatening. But it\'s really hard'

[15:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for a human to actually figure out which mutations are okay, which mutations are not. You see, every human has thousands of genetic variations, and in a sense, we all have different mutations. The overwhelming majority of the time, these'

[16:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mutations don\'t actually cause anything. But the trick is to identify exactly which mutations actually increase the risk of cancer, which is a lot harder said than done. So, the researchers gave Evo 2 this data, and they asked it to'

[16:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'classify which ones are okay, which ones are damaging. Again, note that the model has never been trained on human medical records. It was never given any answers on which genes cause cancer and which'

[16:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t. It doesn\'t even know what cancer is. Yet the results were shocking. The model was able to directly identify the mutations that don\'t do anything and the mutations that cause cancer. So, it'

[16:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'turns out Evo 2 is also a really good detector of cancer just from looking at someone\'s DNA. Now, up to this point, it\'s all analytical. It\'s able to analyze and interpret DNA, but can it generate new functional DNA from'

[16:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scratch? Not just a single protein or tiny gene, but the entire continuous DNA of a living thing? Well, they started with human mitochondria. If you\'re not familiar, mitochondria is the part of'

[17:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your cell that generates energy. Think of it as like the powerhouse of your cell. Now, it turns out that mitochondria have their own DNA that\'s separate from our cells\' DNA. And mitochondria DNA is way smaller. It\'s only roughly 16,000 letters. So, it\'s'

[17:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tiny and manageable, but still quite complex. Now, what the researchers did was it just gave Evo 2 just the first few letters of a human mitochondria genome, and then they asked it to'

[17:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically finish this blueprint. It\'s like giving an AI chatbot the first sentence of an essay and then telling it to finish the essay. And lo and behold, Evo 2 was able to successfully generate a completely new mitochondria sequence'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of roughly 16,000 letters from scratch. Now, generating this DNA is one thing. How do we know if this DNA is actually legit? How do we know if it\'s biologically viable? So, the researchers'

[17:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'used some external validation tools to assess this generation. They started with a tool called MitoZ, which is a well-established software for analyzing this mitochondria DNA. And the results'

[18:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'were astonishing. MitoZ confirmed that Evo 2\'s made-up generation of mitochondria DNA actually contained the correct number of protein-coding genes as well as tRNA genes and rRNA genes, as'

[18:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'expected in real human mitochondria. Now, what exactly do all of these terms mean? Let\'s break this down. So, DNA is, as you know, the master blueprint of life. It contains instructions that tell'

[18:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a cell how to build and operate itself. Now, part of these instructions include how to build proteins, which are like the machines and tools that are used for a cell to function. Now, in order to'

[18:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create these proteins, DNA also needs to code up stuff called ribosomal RNAs, or rRNAs, which are like the factory workers. These are in charge of actually assembling the proteins. And then there'

[19:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are transfer RNAs, which you can think of as like delivery trucks that bring the right raw materials to the assembly line. Each tRNA carries a specific amino acid and places it precisely where it'

[19:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'needs to go according to the instructions. So, DNA basically needs to code up everything for this factory to work. It needs to code up what to create, it needs to code up the delivery system, plus it needs to code up the'

[19:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'factory workers. And all three of these things are crucial for an organism to function and stay alive. Now, what\'s remarkable about Evo 2\'s generation of this imaginary mitochondria is that it'

[19:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'includes all of these features. It includes code on what proteins to build, and also the workers in order to build these proteins, as well as the delivery system. Evo 2 was able to generate a'

[19:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fully working DNA for mitochondria. But the researchers didn\'t stop there. To make sure these proteins and everything else actually work, they next fed this generation through AlphaFold 3. This is'

[20:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the legendary AI from Google DeepMind that predicts how proteins fold into 3D shapes. By the way, let me know in the comments below if you want me to make an explainer video on AlphaFold. I might do one if there is enough interest.'

[20:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Anyways, in short, AlphaFold 3 also confirmed that Evo 2\'s generated proteins actually folded correctly. And what\'s even more important is that these different generated proteins physically'

[20:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interlocked with each other like pieces of a puzzle, exactly as they need to do in real human cells in order to produce energy. So this confirms that this DNA, which was just generated from Evo 2,'

[20:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually works just like in real mitochondria. Okay, so we\'ve proven that Evo 2 can generate the DNA of this organelle. What if we step it up a notch? Can we also get it to generate'

[20:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the complete DNA of a living thing? Well, next the researchers got it to generate the full genome of a bacteria called Mycoplasma genitalium, which looks like this for your reference. Now,'

[21:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the DNA of this is roughly 580,000 letters. And again, the researchers gave it just like the first few letters of this DNA and asked it to generate the rest. And in short, it also succeeded. It was able to generate a complete and'

[21:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fully functional genome that resembles this bacteria in real life. Now, instead of just bacteria, what if we got it to generate something even more complex? So next, the scientists asked Evo 2 to'

[21:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate the entire genome of this other organism called Saccharomyces cerevisiae. This is basically a yeast, which is very different from bacteria. In fact, this organism is more related to humans than'

[21:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it is to bacteria. And again, they just gave it the first few letters of its DNA and then asked it to generate the entire thing. And lo and behold, it was able to successfully generate a fully working DNA of this yeast, complete with the'

[21:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'protein designs, the factory workers, delivery systems, and everything else it needs to function. So this proves that Evo 2 can fluently generate DNA for multiple different types of living'

[22:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things, spanning organelles to bacteria to even yeast. For now, you might have a burning question in your head. If Evo 2 can generate the DNA of existing stuff, can we get it to generate a completely'

[22:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new species? What if we got it to generate a new type of mouse? Or even generate Pokémon? Or even crazier, what if we got it to generate a new type of human? Well, this raises a ton of different bioethic and biosecurity'

[22:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'concerns. So at least for now, at least the researchers weren\'t crazy enough to proceed with that. But speaking of security, here\'s another concern. If this can generate anything, couldn\'t we prompt it to generate a highly'

[22:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'contagious human virus? Well, the good news is the researchers also thought of this beforehand before they trained the model. So they made a very important safety decision right from the start.'

[22:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You see, when they fed it this huge DNA data set of 9 trillion base pairs, they intentionally excluded any sequences of eukaryotic viruses, meaning any virus'

[23:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that can affect humans, animals, or plants. So this includes the most dangerous pathogens listed in the USDA select agents and toxins list. These are like really contagious things that can'

[23:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kill a ton of people. So all this data was excluded from its data set. In other words, the AI was never allowed to learn what these viruses even look like. It\'s like if you were being trained on a'

[23:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'human language, but all the swear words were omitted. You would have no idea what a swear word even is. Now, excluding this training data is one thing. How do they verify that this safety filter actually works? That it'

[23:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can\'t generate viruses. So they used a really standard AI metric called perplexity. No, it\'s not this perplexity. Perplexity is actually a metric which looks at how confused a model is when it encounters something'

[24:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that it hasn\'t seen before. So after training Evo 2, the researchers also gave it the DNA of some human viruses from this list. And basically, its perplexity soared. It was really'

[24:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'confused. It had no understanding of this, no internal framework to make sense of what these sequences are. Now, the researchers went a step further. They also tried to get it to generate the DNA of some dangerous human viruses'

[24:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and see what it would do. Thankfully, the model failed completely. Now, it still generated something, but because it didn\'t have this virus data during training, it just ended up hallucinating'

[24:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and generating gibberish. It was not able to successfully generate the DNA of a legit human virus. Thank goodness for that. Now, the really cool thing is they\'ve actually open-sourced'

[24:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything. So on this GitHub repo, which I\'ll link to in the description below, you can actually download and use Evo 2. So here it contains all the instructions on how to set this up. Now, in addition to just releasing the'

